BREAKING: Rep. Luna Introduces RULES Act to Stop Asylum System Abuse

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE

WASHINGTON, D.C.—Today, Congresswoman Anna Paulina Luna (FL-13) introduced the House companion bill to the Refugees Using Legal Entry Safely (RULES) Act introduced by Senator Bernie Moreno (OH) earlier this year in the United States Senate. This bill seeks to amend the Immigration and Nationality Act to modify the eligibility requirements for asylum, thereby deterring and prohibiting the abuse of the system and ensuring its integrity.

“The days of open-border chaos are over. I’m joining Senator Moreno in introducing the RULES Act to put an end to the rampant fraud and abuse in our asylum system. America is a nation of law and order—not a free-for-all for illegal aliens gaming the system,” said Congresswoman Luna. “If you want asylum in the greatest country on Earth, you follow our rules, period. No more loopholes, no more catch-and-release, no more second chances for lawbreakers. We are taking our border back.”

The introduction of the RULES Act in the House is a decisive step in strengthening the integrity of America’s asylum system. The bill establishes that the only way to claim asylum will be through a legal port of entry in the United States. Additionally, those applying cannot be released or paroled into the country before their cases are adjudicated. Additionally, individuals who have previously been denied asylum will not be able to reapply, and those who have entered the U.S. illegally in the past will be ineligible from applying for this most cherished humanitarian help.

Congresswoman Luna continues her fight to ensure the United States immigration system is under control and protects the interests of the American people.

BREAKING: Rep. Luna Co-Sponsors Bipartisan Legislation Authorizing Additional FEMA Funding Amid Hurricane Helene Disaster

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE

ST. PETERSBURG, FL—Today, Congresswoman Anna Paulina Luna (R, FL-13) co-sponsored bipartisan legislation to support recovery efforts following Hurricane Helene’s devastating impact on Florida and other states across the nation. The bill, introduced by Congressman Jared Moskowitz (D, FL-23), allocates an additional $15 billion in response to Hurricane Helene, including $10 billion for the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) for disaster relief and emergency assistance and $5 billion in supplemental funding to the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) through the Community Development Block Grant Disaster Recovery (CDBG-DR) program.

“My constituents in Pinellas County depend on Congress to take swift and decisive action in the wake of this unprecedented disaster caused by Hurricane Helene,” said Congresswoman Luna. “I am ready and willing to return to Washington and ensure our communities receive the critical resources necessary for a rapid recovery. Americans are counting on us, and we must take immediate action to address their life-saving needs.”

If you need help cleaning up after the storm, this connects you with volunteers from local organizations and faith communities who can assist with tasks like muck outs, tree removal, tarps, and debris.

Volunteers provide tools and equipment at no charge. The hotline will stay open through Friday, October 11, 2024.

⚡️ STAY SAFE: If you are using a generator after losing power, keep it outside in a well-ventilated area, away from doors, windows, and vents.

Never use it in a garage, even with the door open—carbon monoxide can be deadly.

Also, don’t turn your power back on after flooding until an electrician checks your outlets to avoid fire hazards.
